12/11/2003
SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- SFOR announced on Tuesday (11 November) that it has started to destroy vast quantities of unsafe munitions left over from the 1992-1995 conflict. 
A spokesman said that 1,000 tonnes of munitions, mostly belonging to the Bosnian Serb Army, would be destroyed. 
In a separate operation, peacekeepers started to destroy surface-to-air missiles belonging to the armies of the Muslim-Croat and Serb entities.
In other news, a Bosnian Serb Finance Ministry spokeswoman told reporters that Republika Srpska would proceed with plans to raise public sector wages and pensions despite warnings from the IMF and the World Bank. 
The new, higher salaries would be paid out starting next week.
Also Tuesday, the Sarajevo Cantonal Prosecution issued an indictment against Mustafa Hota, a former member of the BiH Army. 
He is accused of killing two Croats in the village of Grabovica in 1993. 
(Dnevni Avaz, Vecernji List, Oslobodjenje - 12/11/03; AFP - 11/11/03)
